1
00:00:38,071 --> 00:00:40,972
I like this for the powder room,
but definitely not the bedroom.

2
00:00:41,074 --> 00:00:42,132
It's a little busy.

3
00:00:42,242 --> 00:00:43,573
I'm not sure.

4
00:00:43,676 --> 00:00:46,144
It's not the curtains
I'm worried about, but the cabinets.

5
00:00:46,246 --> 00:00:48,806
Nixon didn't stand a chance.

6
00:00:48,915 --> 00:00:53,147
The Browns trounced
the Redskins, 31-10.

7
00:00:53,253 --> 00:00:54,880
The result of that last home game

8
00:00:54,988 --> 00:00:58,446
has correctly predicted
the last six elections.

9
00:00:58,558 --> 00:01:01,425
I wish someone would have told me that.

10
00:01:01,528 --> 00:01:05,487
Of course, it's really
a 50/50 chance of being right.

11
00:01:09,569 --> 00:01:15,269
I want to treat you like a son because...
I feel that way towards you.

12
00:01:15,375 --> 00:01:17,468
Okay.

13
00:01:17,577 --> 00:01:20,842
Trudy told us that you
were up for a promotion

14
00:01:20,947 --> 00:01:22,972
and you didn't get it or something.

15
00:01:23,083 --> 00:01:24,550
I wish she hadn't.

16
00:01:24,651 --> 00:01:27,313
Now, she loves you.

17
00:01:27,420 --> 00:01:28,910
And honestly,

18
00:01:29,022 --> 00:01:31,889
I think you need
to take a little focus off your work.

19
00:01:31,991 --> 00:01:35,154
This from one of the top
salesmen at Vicks Chemical.

20
00:01:35,261 --> 00:01:36,558
When you started talking

21
00:01:36,663 --> 00:01:38,790
about that Clearasil
company you bought...

22
00:01:38,898 --> 00:01:40,559
Now, that was kind of
worth bragging about.

23
00:01:40,667 --> 00:01:43,135
Did you know that there's a surge
in adolescence right now?

24
00:01:43,236 --> 00:01:47,263
I'll tell you, Sterling Cooper
and yours truly

25
00:01:47,373 --> 00:01:49,898
would love to help you
deliver that message.

26
00:01:50,009 --> 00:01:52,136
See? Now that's what I'm talking about.

27
00:01:52,245 --> 00:01:54,042
The only family and business
you should be mixing

28
00:01:54,147 --> 00:01:56,615
is the production of a child.

29
00:01:56,716 --> 00:01:58,809
And what did Trudy say about that?

30
00:01:58,918 --> 00:01:59,942
About what?

31
00:02:00,053 --> 00:02:03,784
Tom, loose lips sink ships.

32
00:02:03,890 --> 00:02:05,824
I was just saying that work
isn't everything, you know.

33
00:02:05,925 --> 00:02:09,383
It's like that song says:
Um, tend your own garden.

34
00:02:09,496 --> 00:02:11,157
What song is that, Daddy?

35
00:02:11,264 --> 00:02:12,196
Uh, I don't know.

36
00:02:12,298 --> 00:02:13,265
People say it. It's true.

37
00:02:13,366 --> 00:02:14,333
It is true.

38
00:02:14,434 --> 00:02:15,662
Yeah. Tend to your own garden.

39
00:02:15,768 --> 00:02:19,932
That means... you know,
start growing things.

40
00:02:20,039 --> 00:02:21,404
Daddy!

41
00:02:21,508 --> 00:02:22,736
You're embarrassing us.

42
00:02:22,842 --> 00:02:25,072
It'll be the best Christmas present
this one ever had.

43
00:02:25,178 --> 00:02:26,907
And hell, Thanksgiving's Thursday.

44
00:02:33,186 --> 00:02:37,850
Oh, and I guess I should go to Keppler Farm
to get some acorn squash.

45
00:02:37,957 --> 00:02:40,255
What am I doing?
They have squash there.

46
00:02:40,360 --> 00:02:42,260
Ery good squash, actually.

47
00:02:46,065 --> 00:02:48,431
I wish you would come.

48
00:02:48,535 --> 00:02:51,163
Birdie, I'm a partner.

49
00:02:51,271 --> 00:02:53,865
80% of my business
rolls out next week.

50
00:02:53,973 --> 00:02:55,065
It just seems silly for me

51
00:02:55,175 --> 00:02:58,303
to go down there
for a 12-hour Thanksgiving.

52
00:02:58,411 --> 00:03:03,576
What about... Sally and Bobby's
childhood memories?

53
00:03:05,451 --> 00:03:08,443
There was no reason
you couldn't have it up here.

54
00:03:08,555 --> 00:03:10,455
You know my brother's
children are animals.

55
00:03:10,557 --> 00:03:11,854
They can't make the trip up here,

56
00:03:11,958 --> 00:03:14,483
and I don't want my dad to be alone.

57
00:03:15,195 --> 00:03:20,633
I'll take a cab to the train,
and William will pick us up,

58
00:03:20,733 --> 00:03:22,963
probably in some new car.

59
00:03:28,308 --> 00:03:29,775
You know what? L...

60
00:03:31,211 --> 00:03:33,304
I don't think you want to go.

61
00:03:35,114 --> 00:03:37,275
I'm sorry. Was I unclear about that?

62
00:03:43,056 --> 00:03:44,387
I don't understand

63
00:03:44,490 --> 00:03:47,084
why you can't make
my family your family.

64
00:03:55,768 --> 00:03:58,293
Ken is perfectly happy to have me here.

65
00:04:00,607 --> 00:04:04,703
What do you think it's like?
He's a bachelor. It's dirty.

66
00:04:04,811 --> 00:04:06,642
I'm not complaining.

67
00:04:09,249 --> 00:04:12,480
I don't think it's a good idea
to spend money on a hotel right now.

68
00:04:12,585 --> 00:04:15,554
If you're so worried about my well-being,
let me come home.

69
00:04:18,491 --> 00:04:20,049
That's not what I meant.

70
00:04:22,428 --> 00:04:25,090
I mean, I know how it sounded.

71
00:04:28,635 --> 00:04:30,193
Jennifer.

72
00:04:41,848 --> 00:04:43,008
Yes.

73
00:04:43,116 --> 00:04:45,880
I'll quit if you let me come home.

74
00:04:50,356 --> 00:04:51,948
I miss you...

75
00:04:53,126 --> 00:04:54,923
so much.

76
00:05:08,308 --> 00:05:11,209
Those the legendary
secret files of Bert Cooper?

77
00:05:11,311 --> 00:05:12,437
No.

78
00:05:12,545 --> 00:05:15,605
I got a call from Abraham Menken.

79
00:05:15,715 --> 00:05:17,706
I'm sure you know
that his daughter will be unavailable

80
00:05:17,817 --> 00:05:19,148
for the next three months,

81
00:05:19,252 --> 00:05:24,383
taking some sort of ocean voyage
to Paris and whatnot.

82
00:05:24,490 --> 00:05:26,287
I hadn't heard that.

83
00:05:29,028 --> 00:05:30,256
But otherwise?

84
00:05:30,363 --> 00:05:32,388
There is no otherwise.

85
00:05:32,498 --> 00:05:36,935
Why is this man calling me?

86
00:05:37,036 --> 00:05:39,937
I don't know. Is he unhappy?

87
00:05:40,039 --> 00:05:43,338
As a partner, I do not expect
your personal preferences

88
00:05:43,443 --> 00:05:45,411
to interfere with our business.

89
00:05:45,511 --> 00:05:47,308
Who says they have?

90
00:05:47,413 --> 00:05:49,040
It was the tone of his voice.

91
00:05:49,148 --> 00:05:50,445
He's her father.

92
00:05:50,550 --> 00:05:52,074
That's it, cowboy.

93
00:06:01,461 --> 00:06:02,393
Francine.

94
00:06:02,495 --> 00:06:05,464
I'm coming in. I'm freezing.

95
00:06:07,767 --> 00:06:09,359
You're in your slippers.

96
00:06:09,469 --> 00:06:11,198
I've been outside
waiting for you to come home,

97
00:06:11,304 --> 00:06:14,068
just sitting in the car
hoping no one would see me.

98
00:06:14,173 --> 00:06:15,606
What's going on?

99
00:06:15,708 --> 00:06:17,039
Are your kids home?

100
00:06:17,143 --> 00:06:19,407
No. What happened?

101
00:06:20,747 --> 00:06:22,442
I'm so stupid.

102
00:06:23,616 --> 00:06:25,481
So damn stupid.

103
00:06:26,619 --> 00:06:29,486
You're not, Francine.

104
00:06:29,589 --> 00:06:32,558
Whatever happened, you're not stupid.

105
00:06:32,658 --> 00:06:36,253
My mind hasn't been so sharp
since I had the baby.

106
00:06:36,362 --> 00:06:37,852
And Carlton gave me a stack of mail,

107
00:06:37,964 --> 00:06:40,455
and honestly I think I just threw it away.

108
00:06:40,566 --> 00:06:42,261
And four days later,
the phone was cut off,

109
00:06:42,368 --> 00:06:47,237
so I had to go to the phone company
and pay it, or, you know, he'd have a fit.

110
00:06:47,340 --> 00:06:50,036
And I had to do all this
without him knowing.

111
00:06:50,143 --> 00:06:51,633
How perfect.

112
00:06:54,080 --> 00:06:57,208
I don't understand.

113
00:06:57,316 --> 00:06:58,749
They gave me the bill.

114
00:07:01,754 --> 00:07:05,246
It was close to $18.

115
00:07:05,358 --> 00:07:07,326
There were all these calls:

116
00:07:07,427 --> 00:07:10,328
Long distance, MH.

117
00:07:10,430 --> 00:07:12,830
MH? Manhattan?

118
00:07:15,835 --> 00:07:17,462
So I called one.

119
00:07:19,338 --> 00:07:22,205
A woman answered.

120
00:07:22,308 --> 00:07:24,606
I had just...

121
00:07:24,710 --> 00:07:28,510
I said, "I'm calling
from Carlton Hanson's office. "

122
00:07:28,614 --> 00:07:30,275
She said, "Really?"

123
00:07:30,383 --> 00:07:34,444
I said, "He wants to have dinner
tonight at the usual place. "

124
00:07:34,554 --> 00:07:36,385
What made you say that?

125
00:07:42,195 --> 00:07:46,723
What woman would he
be calling in Manhattan

126
00:07:46,833 --> 00:07:49,324
who answers her own phone?

127
00:07:51,304 --> 00:07:52,862
Married women.

128
00:07:52,972 --> 00:07:56,373
Lots of women answer
their own phones.

129
00:07:56,476 --> 00:07:59,673
So he's calling some married woman
from my house

130
00:07:59,779 --> 00:08:02,907
while I'm upstairs sleeping?

131
00:08:03,015 --> 00:08:05,313
Maybe it's a caterer.

132
00:08:05,418 --> 00:08:08,080
Maybe he's throwing you
a surprise party.

133
00:08:13,493 --> 00:08:18,192
Do you know he spends
two nights a week at the Waldorf?

134
00:08:18,297 --> 00:08:21,289
I'm so stupid.

135
00:08:21,400 --> 00:08:23,163
Assuming the worst...

136
00:08:25,071 --> 00:08:28,040
The worst is that I'll poison him.

137
00:08:28,140 --> 00:08:30,904
He's so stupid, he'd drink anything.

138
00:08:33,913 --> 00:08:37,144
I'm going to have
a house full of people.

139
00:08:37,250 --> 00:08:38,877
I'll poison them all:

140
00:08:38,985 --> 00:08:43,445
His parents, my parents...

141
00:08:43,556 --> 00:08:44,716
my kids.

142
00:08:44,824 --> 00:08:46,223
Stop it.

143
00:08:46,325 --> 00:08:48,589
Stop that, Francine.

144
00:08:49,996 --> 00:08:52,260
You're emotional. It doesn't mean...

145
00:08:52,365 --> 00:08:55,562
Damn it, Betty. I know everything.

146
00:08:55,668 --> 00:08:57,397
What am I going to do?

147
00:08:57,503 --> 00:08:59,698
I've been sitting outside in the car.

148
00:08:59,805 --> 00:09:02,365
What do I do? I thought
you'd know what to do.

149
00:09:04,176 --> 00:09:07,009
Me? L... Why?

150
00:09:10,349 --> 00:09:12,374
I don't know.

151
00:09:22,161 --> 00:09:23,924
I'm s...

152
00:09:24,030 --> 00:09:26,328
so embarrassed.

153
00:09:29,335 --> 00:09:31,360
He doesn't know you know.

154
00:09:31,470 --> 00:09:32,801
I know that.

155
00:09:35,775 --> 00:09:36,764
Go on upstairs.

156
00:09:36,876 --> 00:09:38,275
I should go.

157
00:09:38,377 --> 00:09:40,811
Come on, Bobby,
let's go play in my room.

158
00:09:40,913 --> 00:09:42,938
No. Don't.

159
00:09:43,049 --> 00:09:45,074
It'll be okay.

160
00:09:45,184 --> 00:09:47,880
Mrs. Draper, sorry I'm late.

161
00:09:47,987 --> 00:09:50,979
Oh. It's okay, Carla. You can go.

162
00:09:51,090 --> 00:09:52,557
You want me to unpack the groceries?

163
00:09:52,658 --> 00:09:54,956
I'll do it. Just go.

164
00:09:55,061 --> 00:09:56,858
Good-bye.

165
00:10:47,279 --> 00:10:48,473
First things first.

166
00:10:48,581 --> 00:10:49,946
When I call a meeting,

167
00:10:50,049 --> 00:10:52,574
if you arrive after me, you are late.

168
00:10:53,953 --> 00:10:56,012
Boys, the stock in our stable:

169
00:10:56,122 --> 00:10:59,614
Lucky Strike, Bethlehem Steel, Maytag.

170
00:10:59,725 --> 00:11:03,183
No automobile, airline,
pharmaceuticals.

171
00:11:03,295 --> 00:11:05,889
Tobacco is on that list.

172
00:11:05,998 --> 00:11:07,556
You're Cosgrove, right?

173
00:11:07,667 --> 00:11:11,569
The powerhouse
behind the Rejuvenator?

174
00:11:11,671 --> 00:11:15,198
Actually, it's called
the Relax-a-Cizor now.

175
00:11:15,307 --> 00:11:16,638
What the hell is it?

176
00:11:16,742 --> 00:11:20,337
It's a weight loss device
with a female pleasure payload.

177
00:11:21,480 --> 00:11:22,606
Really?

178
00:11:23,883 --> 00:11:25,475
I'm offering a hundred-dollar bonus

179
00:11:25,584 --> 00:11:29,543
to the first man who brings me
a meeting with a decision maker.

180
00:11:29,655 --> 00:11:33,455
Gentlemen, here's a list of people
you should be having lunch with.

181
00:11:33,559 --> 00:11:36,585
I want you to run into people,
go through old yearbooks.

182
00:11:36,696 --> 00:11:39,665
This means everybody. Writers, too.

183
00:11:39,765 --> 00:11:41,164
Bringing in business is the key

184
00:11:41,267 --> 00:11:43,929
to your salary, your status,
and your self-worth.

185
00:11:44,036 --> 00:11:45,628
I went to the Athletic Club today,

186
00:11:45,738 --> 00:11:48,536
and I sat in the steam
for an hour and a half.

187
00:11:48,641 --> 00:11:50,199
In that time, I lost 4 pounds

188
00:11:50,309 --> 00:11:52,038
and learned that Kodak still isn't happy

189
00:11:52,144 --> 00:11:54,044
with the campaign
for the new slide projector.

190
00:11:54,146 --> 00:11:56,410
Is any of this sinking in?

191
00:12:00,519 --> 00:12:03,545
"It's true that while simply relaxing,

192
00:12:03,656 --> 00:12:06,420
"I can get all the benefits
of calisthenics.

193
00:12:06,525 --> 00:12:09,926
"A simple regimen of three
20-minute sessions per week,

194
00:12:10,029 --> 00:12:11,826
"combined with a sensible diet,

195
00:12:11,931 --> 00:12:14,058
"will restore your youthful glow.

196
00:12:14,166 --> 00:12:16,930
"I love the way it makes me feel.

197
00:12:17,036 --> 00:12:18,469
"The Relax-a-Cizor.

198
00:12:18,571 --> 00:12:20,664
It's my little secret. "

199
00:12:22,174 --> 00:12:24,404
Thank you, Annie.

200
00:12:24,510 --> 00:12:28,173
Uh, one more time... Rita.

201
00:12:29,448 --> 00:12:31,416
"I never thought it would happen to me,

202
00:12:31,517 --> 00:12:34,384
"but I regained my youth
and my happiness.

203
00:12:34,487 --> 00:12:36,250
- Just ask my husband. "
- Todd?

204
00:12:36,355 --> 00:12:38,380
I think we're both going
to agree on Annie.

205
00:12:38,491 --> 00:12:39,822
Which one is Annie?

206
00:12:41,393 --> 00:12:43,486
Believe it or not, I like Rita.

207
00:12:43,596 --> 00:12:47,225
She's got that voice:
Randy and knowing,

208
00:12:47,333 --> 00:12:48,732
like the Relax-a-Cizor.

209
00:12:48,834 --> 00:12:52,326
Annie belongs on TV
with Rita's voice dubbed in.

210
00:12:55,007 --> 00:12:56,031
Norma, thank you.

211
00:12:56,142 --> 00:12:57,166
You can go.

212
00:12:59,578 --> 00:13:00,840
Whatever the...

213
00:13:00,946 --> 00:13:04,313
special properties
of the Relax-a-Cizor are,

214
00:13:04,416 --> 00:13:08,750
what we are selling is confidence,
a better you.

215
00:13:08,854 --> 00:13:10,515
That woman isn't a better anything.

216
00:13:10,623 --> 00:13:16,084
Annie is a confident, beautiful woman,
and you can hear it in her voice.

217
00:13:16,195 --> 00:13:18,663
I can't believe I'm in this argument.

218
00:13:18,764 --> 00:13:20,493
Sorry about that, Rita.

219
00:13:20,599 --> 00:13:22,590
Hi, Annie. We'll do this tomorrow.

220
00:13:22,701 --> 00:13:24,100
Check with Peggy here
for your session.

221
00:13:26,972 --> 00:13:28,530
If I get a hard time about this,

222
00:13:28,641 --> 00:13:30,040
I'm telling people it was your idea.

223
00:13:30,142 --> 00:13:32,007
It was my idea.

224
00:13:46,058 --> 00:13:49,118
Just a minute. I'll be right back.

225
00:13:52,598 --> 00:13:54,998
Do you have to?

226
00:13:55,100 --> 00:13:57,728
Peter.

227
00:13:57,837 --> 00:14:01,238
That's risky business.

228
00:14:01,340 --> 00:14:03,501
It is, isn't it?

229
00:14:07,513 --> 00:14:10,175
What, honey?

230
00:14:10,282 --> 00:14:12,409
You can say anything to me.

231
00:14:19,558 --> 00:14:24,996
I can't provide for a child
on what I make.

232
00:14:26,565 --> 00:14:28,430
Don't worry about that.

233
00:14:32,037 --> 00:14:34,471
How could I not?

234
00:14:34,573 --> 00:14:36,302
You can't.

235
00:14:37,776 --> 00:14:39,869
Really?

236
00:14:39,979 --> 00:14:42,573
You can't worry about that.

237
00:14:52,458 --> 00:14:54,392
So stay here.

238
00:15:04,403 --> 00:15:07,736
Oh... Peter.

239
00:15:22,588 --> 00:15:23,555
Hi, Birdie.

240
00:15:28,627 --> 00:15:31,460
It's 9:30. Why didn't you
just stay in the city?

241
00:15:31,563 --> 00:15:35,090
Oh, I have work to do here as well.

242
00:15:35,200 --> 00:15:38,465
Do you know where
the slide projector is?

243
00:15:38,570 --> 00:15:40,834
So you're not going
to see us for four days,

244
00:15:40,940 --> 00:15:42,703
and you're not going to see us now.

245
00:15:42,808 --> 00:15:44,537
Bets, right when I walk in the door?

246
00:15:48,113 --> 00:15:49,410
I'm sorry.

247
00:15:51,116 --> 00:15:54,142
I'm sorry. I just... I had a terrible day.

248
00:15:57,256 --> 00:15:59,417
Sit with me.

249
00:16:08,200 --> 00:16:09,258
What happened?

250
00:16:13,439 --> 00:16:14,565
Francine told me

251
00:16:14,673 --> 00:16:16,504
Carlton has been having an affair.

252
00:16:18,444 --> 00:16:20,571
Really?

253
00:16:22,147 --> 00:16:23,705
She was in pieces, Don.

254
00:16:23,816 --> 00:16:25,010
I didn't know what to say to her.

255
00:16:25,117 --> 00:16:28,052
Well, what could you say?

256
00:16:28,153 --> 00:16:29,711
I'm surprised she told you.

257
00:16:29,822 --> 00:16:31,585
Why?

258
00:16:31,690 --> 00:16:33,817
She's like a sister to me.

259
00:16:33,926 --> 00:16:36,087
Of course she is.

260
00:16:41,433 --> 00:16:43,594
I never liked Carlton.

261
00:16:43,702 --> 00:16:46,762
He was never my favorite.

262
00:16:46,872 --> 00:16:49,272
She should poison him.

263
00:16:49,375 --> 00:16:52,003
Now you think she should kill him?

264
